pr_title: Add realm owner feature.
pr_body:
<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->
This PR has backend code for realm owner feature.
 

- The user who creates the realm is made realm owner.
- Migration is written to make oldest realm admin as realm owner for existing realms.
- Add or remove realm owner status of user.
- Last realm owner cannot be removed from realm owner status and also cannot be deactivated from realm.

**Testing Plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->


**GIFs or Screenshots:** <!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html
  -->


<!-- Also be sure to make clear, coherent commits:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing/version-control.html
  -->

- More than one value cannot be true.
- Existing role should also be set to false along with the new role passed as true.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 27, 21, 29, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sahil839', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 431454118, 'comment_body': 'Conditions here are bit different and complicated because `is_realm_admin` is true for both admins and owners.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 27, 21, 30, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sahil839', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 431470365, 'comment_body': 'I was not sure whether we want to add setter for this as it was not required till now.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 27, 22, 7, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sahil839', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 431483548, 'comment_body': 'Let's consistently say "target user is an organization owner."  -- i.e. always put the "organization" word in there.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 27, 22, 42, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 431485068, 'comment_body': 'Remove the extra space. I'd like us to create a `def parse_requested_role(is_owner, is_admin, is_guest)` that just looks at those properties to determine what role was requested (if any of them is not None) and returns that.  And then we can do a single conditional comparing it with `user_profile.role` to determine whether we need to change the role.

Once we've isolated that, we can open a separate follow-up issue for allowing accepting a `role` parameter in the API, with that `parse_requested_role` function present for backwards-compatibility.

We should do this as a new first commit with just the `is_admin` and `is_guest` parameters, that we can merge happily, and then a small tweak on top of that to pass the new `is_owner` option.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 27, 23, 1, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 431491196, 'comment_body': 'Why did you remove this? pr_title: realm owner: Change desdemona to owner and add is_owner field to user objects.
pr_body:
<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->
This PR has four commits on the basis of this [comment](https://github.com/zulip/zulip/pull/15116#issuecomment-636561477).

- First commit is just one line change which changes `is_admin` in `format_user_row` to return
`is_admin` as True for owners also which removes the changes in test as mentioned [here](https://github.com/zulip/zulip/pull/15116#discussion_r431491412).
- Second commit changes desdemona to owner.
- Third commit changes dev env login page to show desdemona as owner instead of admin,
- Fourth commit adds `is_owner` field to the user objects returned by get endpoints for users.


**Testing Plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->


**GIFs or Screenshots:** <!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html
  -->


<!-- Also be sure to make clear, coherent commits:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing/version-control.html
  -->
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 433524097, 'comment_body': 'Your original version of this commit added lines to "Feature level 7".  You should never add new changes to the documentation for an existing feature level already declared in `version.py`.  Except in rare cases (like what we did with 7), each API change should get its own feature level entry.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 1, 22, 31, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 433524428, 'comment_body': 'Okay, I will keep this in mind from next time.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 1, 22, 32, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sahil839', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 433524829, 'comment_body': 'Any changes to `zulip.yaml` as part of an API changed need a `**Changes**:` entry.  I added this one:

```
+
+            **Changes**: New in Zulip 2.2 (feature level 8).
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 1, 22, 33, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 433525447, 'comment_body': 'Yeah, will be taken care from next time.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 1, 22, 35, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sahil839', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: slack_import: Map slack owners to zulip owners.
pr_body:
Slack owners and priamry owners will be mapped to zulip
realm owners on import.

Previously, we mapped the owner and primary owner roles of slack
to ROLE_REALM_ADMINISTRATOR in zulip. As we have added
ROLE_REALM_OWNER in 8bbc074, we now map slack owners and primary
owners to owners in zulip.

Tests are modified for checking all the 3 cases-
 - Slack workspace primary owner
 - Slack workspace owner
 - Slack workspace admin

This commit also has docs change in 'import_from_slack.md'.

<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->

pr_title: invite: Add option to invite user as an organization owner.
pr_body:
We can now invite new users as realm owner. We restrict only
owners to invite new users as owners both for single invite
and multiuse invite link. Also, only owners can revoke or resend
owner invitations.

pr_title: Implement concept of stream admin
pr_body:
<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->
This PR is for implementing concept of stream admin,

- [x] Add a role field to subscription model. (merged)
- [x] Allow stream admins to update stream properties and to deactivate a stream.(merged)
- [x] Allow stream admin to remove others from stream.(merged)
- [x] Add `is_stream_admin` field to Subscription objects sent to clients.(merged)
- [x] Allow stream admin to change stream properties from UI.
- [x] Prevent unsubscribing of last stream admin.
- [x] Change role from stream admin to role if stream admin unsubscribes.
- [x] Make creator of stream a stream admin.
- [x] Add API endpoint to change the role of user in stream.
- [x] Add `stream_admins` field to Subscription objects passed to clients.
- [ ] Add indicator for stream admin subscribers list.
- [ ] UI for changing subscription role.

<!-- How have you tested? -->


<!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html
  -->


<!-- Also be sure to make clear, coherent commits:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing/version-control.html

Also, here there can be multiple streams and multiple users, so I am checking for each stream whether all the admins of that streams are removed. Do you mean I should instead have a loop on stream and then check wheter the set of users of for that stream contains the set of admins or not? I am not clear what should be the change exactly.

Also, I cannot find any commit here for squashing.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 2, 24, 6, 56, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sahil839', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 582228064, 'comment_body': '@timabbott I agree with sending only ids in event, should we also change the event dict sent from `do_change_subscription_property` to only send id and not user email or stream name. I am suggesting this because event sent from `do_change_subscription_role` and `do_change_subscription_property` have same event `type=subscription` and `op=update` and the openapi schema is not validating in tests because both functions send different details in event objects. There is another way by sending the different event type for role case, but I think we would eventually prefer only ids and not stream name and user email.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 2, 24, 19, 8, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sahil839', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: stream: Allow non admins to set stream post policy when creating streams
pr_body:
This PR allows non admins to set stream post policy while creating
streams.

Restriction was there to prevent user from creating a stream in which
the user cannot post himself but this will be taken care of with
stream admin feature.

Removed the tests as there is no restrciction now for creation of streams and users can create streams with all stream_post_policy values.

pr_title: Add support for setting message retention policy for individual streams.
pr_body:
<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->
This adds support for setting message retention policy for individual streams.
Only admins are allowed to change it or set it while creating streams.



**Testing Plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->

(GitHub real-time page update is kinda broken, that's why I didn't notice you reply)

yes, that's true, I was saying from a developers perspective and maybe from API standpoint too, that `-1` at `Stream` side means something else. Related discussion: https://github.com/zulip/zulip/pull/14903#issuecomment-626204683
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 17, 13, 9, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'pragatiagrawal31', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 441538153, 'comment_body': 'Yeah -1 for stream means we will retain forever inspite of realm-setting value being a finite postive number.

`Realm.message_retention_days` being NULL means the natural thing "no realm-wide policy set", which is the default situation and we're not archiving old messages. So then, if a stream sets its retention policy then we're going to archive the stream's messages according to that - there's no contradiction with the realm's policy because the realm has no policy.

Similarly  `Stream.message_retention_days` being NULL means "no stream policy set", so we just take the realm policy, if any.

Streams have the special option of declaring "keep my messages forever" (through the value `-1`), because that's something potentially useful if the admin wants to exclude certain streams from the realm-wide policy. pr_title: message_events: Fix live update of message edit history.
pr_body:
This PR adds code to live update the message edit histroy.
Message edit histroy is fetched and rendered again if the edit
histroy modal is open.

Fixes #15051.

<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->


<!-- How have you tested? -->


<!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html
  -->


<!-- Also be sure to make clear, coherent commits:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing/version-control.html
  -->
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 429686327, 'comment_body': "This needs to check that the message that was just edited is the same as the one we're currently looking at message-edit history for.  Otherwise, it'll generate wrong behavior.

My guess is we can also use something in `overlay.js` to check if the overlay is open?  But maybe that doesn't matter because we want to check if it's open to a given message, and doing that will require exporting some state from `message_edit.js`.

@sahil839 I'd like to get you into the habit of thinking about and testing corner cases like this -- it's really important to writing correct code.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 24, 23, 36, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 430050431, 'comment_body': '@timabbott I will definitely try to cover most of the corner cases in first time itself.

I was not able to find any exisiting way to check that edit history modal is of which message, so I added code to add `data-message-id` attr while openign the modal.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 25, 19, 8, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sahil839', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: stream_edit: Use user_ids for subscribing/unsubscribing to a stream.
pr_body:
This PR changes the code of subscibing/unsusbscribing to a
stream to use user_ids instead of emails.

pr_title: invites: Send user_id of the referrer instead of email in invites dict.
pr_body:
We send user_id of the referrer instead of email in the invites dict.
Sending user_ids is more robust, as those are an immutable reference
to a user, rather than something that can change with time.

I am waiting for #15574 to merge before changing the UI to display name of the referrer instead of email with the user popover.

<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->

functions for them rather than stubs.

pr_title: stream_edit: Send values of changed settings only to backend.
pr_body:
This PR changes change_stream_privacy function to only
send the values of changed settings to backend.
We also avoid sending PATCH request if none of the settings
in stream privacy modal are changed.

This change also fixes the bug in changing stream permissions
for realms with limited plans.

Fixes #16024.

for elements to get hidden. Using 'visible: false' just checks

the element is hidden or not.

pr_title: emails: Add quote prefix ">" in plain text missed message emails.
pr_body:
We add quote prefix ">" to each line of the message in the plain text
missed message emails, which are then rendered as quotes by email
clients. We also move the message content in the next line after sender.

This helps us in clearly showing the message authors in missed message
emails especially in emails with multiple messages and senders.

Fixes #15836.

<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->

We show a modal as a warning when unsubscribing a private stream
because it is a reversible action and one cannot re-subscribe to
it until added by other members of the stream.

I have used two different classes for the button in modal because we show
success message below the add subscribers input only when we unsubscribe 
from subscriber list.

pr_title: Fix error message for deactivating the last oraganization owner.
pr_body:
This PR fixes-
- Error message shown when deactivating the last owner to show "Cannot deactivate
the last organization owner" instead of "Cannot deactivate the last organization administrator".
- Example for "400" responses of deactivate user endpoints to show msg as "Cannot deactivate
the last organization owner" instead of "Cannot deactivate the last organization administrator"

pr_title: message_list: Live update trailing bookend on stream deactivation.
pr_body:
We were not updating the trailing bookend on deactivation of stream
if the user was narrowed to deactivated stream and this commit fixes
this.

For subscribed streams, we just show the trailing bookend with
content as 'This stream has been deactivated' and hide the
Unsubscribe button.

For unsubscribed streams, we change the content of trailing bookend
to 'This stream has been deactivated' and hide the Subscribe button.

Fixes #15999.

<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->


**Testing Plan:** <!-- How have you tested? --> Tested manually in the development environment.
